WEBVTT

00:00:20.260 --> 00:00:21.830
From London-- join students

00:00:21.830 --> 00:00:24.430
from the London Business School
for C.E.O. EXCHANGE.

00:00:24.430 --> 00:00:29.900
It's a city of contrasts.

00:00:29.900 --> 00:00:32.960
Tradition abounds...

00:00:32.960 --> 00:00:37.130
yet net fever
has taken London by the reins.

00:00:37.130 --> 00:00:39.860
Meet two C.E.O.s helping turn
the Old World new.

00:00:39.860 --> 00:00:42.730
Those words weren't even in
our vocabulary eight months ago.

00:00:42.730 --> 00:00:45.730
Jim Rose of the on-line
auction site QXL.com

00:00:45.730 --> 00:00:47.800
and Kevin Roberts
of advertising giant

00:00:47.800 --> 00:00:50.360
Saatchi  and  Saatchi are high-tech
with a British accent.

00:00:50.360 --> 00:00:52.830
Once we can connect
emotionally on the net

00:00:52.830 --> 00:00:55.030
it will become
a more powerful medium.

00:00:55.030 --> 00:01:01.000
Next, two C.E.O.s driving
forces in Europe and beyond.

00:01:01.000 --> 00:01:03.230
Exclusive national funding
is provideby A.T. KEARNEY]

00:01:03.230 --> 00:01:06.060
They're called innovators;

00:01:06.060 --> 00:01:08.400
big thinkers;

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:09.730
the leaders;

00:01:09.730 --> 00:01:13.230
the ones who push
when others pull.

00:01:13.230 --> 00:01:17.530
Some transform industry,
other change society.

00:01:17.530 --> 00:01:20.400
Many inspire a new generation.

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:23.400
C.E.O.s,
Chief Executive Officers

00:01:23.400 --> 00:01:26.260
facing challenges,
achieving success

00:01:26.260 --> 00:01:31.030
telling their stories.

00:01:31.030 --> 00:01:32.560
And now our host

00:01:32.560 --> 00:01:35.900
CNN's senior analyst,
Jeff Greenfield.

00:01:35.900 --> 00:01:46.160
( applause )

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:49.100
Thank you
and welcome to C.E.O. Exchange.

00:01:49.100 --> 00:01:51.860
It is a blow to my American
arrogance to admit this

00:01:51.860 --> 00:01:54.230
but coming to Europe
sometimes makes me feel

00:01:54.230 --> 00:01:56.800
like I have landed in
an advanced civilization.

00:01:56.800 --> 00:01:58.900
You have high-speed trains,
the Chunnel

00:01:58.900 --> 00:02:00.730
digital television in the home

00:02:00.730 --> 00:02:03.330
the best wireless phone networks
on earth.

00:02:03.330 --> 00:02:06.460
But when it comes to the web,
it is different.

00:02:06.460 --> 00:02:09.860
The earthquake that has shaken
the American business landscape

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:12.400
to its roots is still
more or less a tremor here.

00:02:12.400 --> 00:02:15.730
Jim Rose is one of the people
who wants to change all that.

00:02:15.730 --> 00:02:18.460
Since 1999,
he has been C.E.O. of QXL.com

00:02:18.460 --> 00:02:22.530
the on-line auction company
that is now one of the top three

00:02:22.530 --> 00:02:24.960
internet retailing sites
in the U.K.

00:02:24.960 --> 00:02:28.160
His company is a striking
example of the challenge

00:02:28.160 --> 00:02:30.200
posed by Europe and its culture

00:02:30.200 --> 00:02:32.700
to the so-called
"instant global medium."

00:02:32.700 --> 00:02:35.630
We will meet Jim Rose of QXL.com
later in the show.

00:02:35.630 --> 00:02:38.630
But first, Kevin Roberts
of Saatchi  and  Saatchi.

00:02:38.630 --> 00:02:41.130
Internet companies
proclaim themselves

00:02:41.130 --> 00:02:42.760
heralds of the new media

00:02:42.760 --> 00:02:46.360
but they are pouring money
into the old media to do it.

00:02:46.360 --> 00:02:48.700
That's one reason
why ad agencies

00:02:48.700 --> 00:02:50.100
are enjoying boom times.

00:02:50.100 --> 00:02:52.660
More than a C.E.O.,
Roberts is an evangelist.

00:02:52.660 --> 00:02:54.430
He literally travels the world

00:02:54.430 --> 00:02:56.560
preaching the gospel
of brand loyalty

00:02:56.560 --> 00:03:00.760
and the perils and promise
of the future.

00:03:00.760 --> 00:03:02.330
How you doing, guys?

00:03:02.330 --> 00:03:05.260
Announcer:
Behind Kevin Roberts
are 7,000 employees

00:03:05.260 --> 00:03:07.160
in 150 Saatchi  and  Saatchi offices

00:03:07.160 --> 00:03:09.100
in 92 countries
around the world.

00:03:09.100 --> 00:03:11.200
An "A" list
of international clients

00:03:11.200 --> 00:03:14.700
includes Procter  and  Gamble,
Toyota, Sony and Hewlett-Packard

00:03:14.700 --> 00:03:16.330
with international billings

00:03:16.330 --> 00:03:18.600
of over seven billion dollars
in 1999.

00:03:18.600 --> 00:03:21.130
Ahead of Mr. Roberts
is the high-profile merger

00:03:21.130 --> 00:03:24.000
with Publicist, the biggest
French advertising agency

00:03:24.000 --> 00:03:26.230
which recently bought
Saatchi  and  Saatchi

00:03:26.230 --> 00:03:28.230
for two billion dollars.

00:03:28.230 --> 00:03:30.360
They did some fantastic
media ideas, right?

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:32.600
Roberts:
There's going to be
a new revolution.

00:03:32.600 --> 00:03:34.500
We've gone through
the Information Age

00:03:34.500 --> 00:03:36.200
we're past
the Age of Knowledge.

00:03:36.200 --> 00:03:38.800
That's not enough
for today's consumers.

00:03:38.800 --> 00:03:41.530
They are very cynical,
they are very savvy

00:03:41.530 --> 00:03:43.260
they are very experienced.

00:03:43.260 --> 00:03:46.860
Now you have to establish
trust and lust.

00:03:46.860 --> 00:03:48.860
Smooth those
out more... okay.

00:03:48.860 --> 00:03:52.130
Announcer:
Before Roberts came on board
as C.E.O. in 1997

00:03:52.130 --> 00:03:54.930
big name brands were deserting
Saatchi  and  Saatchi--

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:56.630
revenues were falling.

00:03:56.630 --> 00:03:59.530
In came Roberts who had never
worked in advertising before.

00:03:59.530 --> 00:04:03.260
Roberts:
The first thing I did was
to really reinforce the values

00:04:03.260 --> 00:04:06.630
that were already there: that
"nothing is impossible" credo;

00:04:06.630 --> 00:04:08.660
the belief that
Saatchi  and  Saatchi wanted to be

00:04:08.660 --> 00:04:11.900
revered as a hothouse for
world-changing creative ideas.

00:04:11.900 --> 00:04:15.630
I didn't bring in
any new people at all.

00:04:15.630 --> 00:04:17.800
I did it with the team
that was there.

00:04:17.800 --> 00:04:21.830
And that shows, you know,
what strong people we had.

00:04:21.830 --> 00:04:23.730
Announcer:
Since Roberts took over
as C.E.O.

00:04:23.730 --> 00:04:25.460
Saatchi  and  Saatchi has built
on results

00:04:25.460 --> 00:04:26.630
rather than on commission

00:04:26.630 --> 00:04:28.700
and revenues are up ten percent.

00:04:28.700 --> 00:04:30.660
Man:
There has been a steady increase

00:04:30.660 --> 00:04:33.630
in the net new billings
over the years

00:04:33.630 --> 00:04:38.100
to a record $735 million
in 1999.

00:04:38.100 --> 00:04:41.260
It was an absolutely stunning
performance.

00:04:41.260 --> 00:04:43.430
They are winning new clients.

00:04:43.430 --> 00:04:45.600
Announcer:
But those clients can be fickle.

00:04:45.600 --> 00:04:48.430
In spite of record
new client gains last year

00:04:48.430 --> 00:04:52.100
Saatchi  and  Saatchi lost
the most international business

00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:54.530
of all advertising agencies,
$326 million.

00:04:54.530 --> 00:04:58.230
Constant focus on key clients
is what drives Roberts.

00:04:58.230 --> 00:05:01.700
Roberts:
I don't waste any time
worrying about losing them.

00:05:01.700 --> 00:05:03.460
I spend my time worrying about

00:05:03.460 --> 00:05:05.230
how to grow
their business faster.

00:05:05.230 --> 00:05:07.960
Announcer:
Which explains a lot
about his passion for China

00:05:07.960 --> 00:05:10.830
currently the eighth largest
advertising market in the world.

00:05:10.830 --> 00:05:13.530
Roberts:
Saatchi  and  Saatchi is the biggest
agency in China.

00:05:13.530 --> 00:05:16.030
We've been there through
rough and rougher.

00:05:16.030 --> 00:05:19.300
And we'll be there for rough,
rough and even more rough

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:22.830
because the opportunity,
the potential is fantastic.

00:05:22.830 --> 00:05:25.630
Announcer:
Opportunity knocked for Roberts
when the high school grad

00:05:25.630 --> 00:05:27.960
met '60s fashion legend
Mary Quant in a bar.

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:31.530
The next day he was running
her cosmetics division.

00:05:31.530 --> 00:05:33.860
Roberts:
You got dragged in for this
as well, did you?

00:05:33.860 --> 00:05:36.330
Announcer:
As C.E.O.,
Roberts has headed up Pepsi

00:05:36.330 --> 00:05:37.960
in the Middle East and Canada

00:05:37.960 --> 00:05:40.960
where Pepsi outstripped sales
of Coke under his leadership.

00:05:40.960 --> 00:05:42.900
In 1989, he moved his family
to New Zealand

00:05:42.900 --> 00:05:45.930
the place he calls home,
when he became C.E.O.

00:05:45.930 --> 00:05:49.060
of the Lyon Nathan Brewery
and quadrupled their profits.

00:05:49.060 --> 00:05:52.030
We bring more emotion
and more warmth into stuff

00:05:52.030 --> 00:05:53.430
which is where this is going.

00:05:53.430 --> 00:05:55.230
Announcer:
Taking on a New Zealand accent

00:05:55.230 --> 00:05:57.700
along with the directorship
of a rugby club

00:05:57.700 --> 00:05:59.530
he has co-written a book

00:05:59.530 --> 00:06:02.760
equating the strengths
of good management and sports.

00:06:02.760 --> 00:06:04.360
Ever ahead
of building new business

00:06:04.360 --> 00:06:06.730
Kevin Roberts's other passions
are his family

00:06:06.730 --> 00:06:09.560
playing tennis, watching rugby
and collecting art--

00:06:09.560 --> 00:06:11.100
a lot of art.

00:06:11.100 --> 00:06:12.530
A lifestyle far removed

00:06:12.530 --> 00:06:15.100
from his working-class
background growing up in England

00:06:15.100 --> 00:06:17.030
and better suited
to the goal he achieved

00:06:17.030 --> 00:06:19.300
of becoming a millionaire
by the time he was 30

00:06:19.300 --> 00:06:23.130
a goal as bold and inspired
as the art he collects.

00:06:23.130 --> 00:06:26.060
Greenfield:
As we say in the States,
"let's get ready to rumble."

00:06:26.060 --> 00:06:28.200
Ladies and gentlemen,
please welcome

00:06:28.200 --> 00:06:31.060
the C.E.O. of Saatchi  and  Saatchi,
Kevin Roberts.

00:06:31.060 --> 00:06:36.100
( applause )

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:49.800
Have a seat.

00:06:49.800 --> 00:06:52.060
Fo
( smattering of applause )

00:06:52.060 --> 00:06:54.500
Okay.

00:06:54.500 --> 00:06:56.400
It's odd that we're
putting this
on the table

00:06:56.400 --> 00:06:58.130
since we are in
front of an audience

00:06:58.130 --> 00:06:59.560
of business school folks

00:06:59.560 --> 00:07:02.100
but college was
something you skipped
entirely, right?

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:05.100
Yeah-- I would never recommend
it in today's age

00:07:05.100 --> 00:07:06.400
I think it was...

00:07:06.400 --> 00:07:08.730
In the 60's, it was all about
growth and luck

00:07:08.730 --> 00:07:10.460
and opportunity and a lot of...

00:07:10.460 --> 00:07:11.800
a creative explosion,
right?

00:07:11.800 --> 00:07:13.230
Greenfield:
I'm still
wrestling

00:07:13.230 --> 00:07:15.360
with this story and
the greater moral of it.

00:07:15.360 --> 00:07:17.260
Let me see if I can
at least find one.

00:07:17.260 --> 00:07:20.300
When you now are
the C.E.O. of a company

00:07:20.300 --> 00:07:23.430
that I assume employs
a great many people

00:07:23.430 --> 00:07:25.160
with high university
education

00:07:25.160 --> 00:07:26.760
and graduate
degrees and all

00:07:26.760 --> 00:07:29.760
what, if any, role
does this educational
background

00:07:29.760 --> 00:07:32.060
or lack of it have
in how you lead now?

00:07:32.060 --> 00:07:33.600
When we hire people

00:07:33.600 --> 00:07:36.330
at Saatchi  and  Saatchi we are just
looking for a couple of things:

00:07:36.330 --> 00:07:37.560
One, are they team players?

00:07:37.560 --> 00:07:39.130
You know,
do they work in a team?

00:07:39.130 --> 00:07:40.500
Because we don't like these

00:07:40.500 --> 00:07:42.330
kind of...
disruptive influences.

00:07:42.330 --> 00:07:45.100
We like people who are
disruptive within a team.

00:07:45.100 --> 00:07:47.200
So, it's kind of
one team, one dream.

00:07:47.200 --> 00:07:49.560
We look for people
who are competitive

00:07:49.560 --> 00:07:51.200
passionate and restless

00:07:51.200 --> 00:07:54.400
people who are driven
by emotion

00:07:54.400 --> 00:07:58.460
rather than by logic
and rational stuff.

00:07:58.460 --> 00:08:01.330
We just hired
some account executives

00:08:01.330 --> 00:08:05.130
and we put this ad in the paper
with no logo on it.

00:08:05.130 --> 00:08:07.860
We just put,
"Would you like to join

00:08:07.860 --> 00:08:12.430
the hottest idea shop
on the planet?"

00:08:12.430 --> 00:08:14.860
So we got a lot
of people who were
crazy enough to apply.

00:08:14.860 --> 00:08:17.430
And then we said, "Okay,
we're at Saatchi  and  Saatchi.

00:08:17.430 --> 00:08:19.330
Come in for an interview
tomorrow."

00:08:19.330 --> 00:08:21.300
So a lot of people
came in, kids.

00:08:21.300 --> 00:08:24.860
We didn't ask them where
they'd been to school
or what they did.

00:08:24.860 --> 00:08:27.500
We just gave them all
a Polaroid camera
and said

00:08:27.500 --> 00:08:29.660
"Come back tomorrow
with three pictures

00:08:29.660 --> 00:08:33.430
that are going
to change the world."

00:08:33.430 --> 00:08:35.160
And this New Zealand kid, 22

00:08:35.160 --> 00:08:38.700
came back in with three pictures
of himself.

00:08:38.700 --> 00:08:41.160
Greenfield:
Did you hire him?

00:08:41.160 --> 00:08:44.400
We hired him and we've
promoted him twice
in two years.

00:08:44.400 --> 00:08:47.300
Not because he comes from
New Zealand, entirely.

00:08:47.300 --> 00:08:49.900
To me, to me, though,
this is

00:08:49.900 --> 00:08:52.730
a striking illustration
of what, I gather, is

00:08:52.730 --> 00:08:56.700
at the core of your...
professional life.

00:08:56.700 --> 00:08:58.100
That is...
Lunacy.

00:08:58.100 --> 00:08:59.630
No, I wouldn't
put it that way

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:01.230
although, I'll take
your guidance.

00:09:01.230 --> 00:09:03.730
I was thinking more
of the instinct,
the emotion

00:09:03.730 --> 00:09:05.260
as you say,
the non-rational.

00:09:05.260 --> 00:09:07.560
And my question
to you is,
as a C.E.O.

00:09:07.560 --> 00:09:09.930
of a worldwide company,
are there times

00:09:09.930 --> 00:09:12.200
when you have to
do it the other way?

00:09:12.200 --> 00:09:14.100
When you have
to be methodical?

00:09:14.100 --> 00:09:15.860
If you are looking
at budgets

00:09:15.860 --> 00:09:18.900
if you are looking
at decisions that
involve money

00:09:18.900 --> 00:09:20.860
or can you always
be this person

00:09:20.860 --> 00:09:23.660
who is thinking in
this intuitive, hunch way?

00:09:23.660 --> 00:09:25.900
When I joined the company
the first thing I did

00:09:25.900 --> 00:09:28.030
was get rid of
the human resource department

00:09:28.030 --> 00:09:30.960
and the second thing I did was
get rid of the budget process.

00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:32.660
So we don't do
that stuff anymore.

00:09:32.660 --> 00:09:33.630
( laughter )

00:09:33.630 --> 00:09:34.900
So when I go
to an agency

00:09:34.900 --> 00:09:36.300
I just look at the work.

00:09:36.300 --> 00:09:38.630
If the work is great
we are going to make money.

00:09:38.630 --> 00:09:40.660
You know,
this is a real simple business--

00:09:40.660 --> 00:09:42.360
do great work,
look for imagination

00:09:42.360 --> 00:09:44.030
look for intuition,
look for ideas.

00:09:44.030 --> 00:09:45.900
They are all
kind of "I" words, right?

00:09:45.900 --> 00:09:49.160
Then look for "E" words like
emotion, excitement
and energy.

00:09:49.160 --> 00:09:51.030
And if all that stuff
is happening

00:09:51.030 --> 00:09:53.460
you are going to make
bucket loads of dough.

00:09:53.460 --> 00:09:55.730
Couple more things before
we bring out our next guest

00:09:55.730 --> 00:09:57.160
and then you're going
to come back

00:09:57.160 --> 00:09:58.900
and we're going
to really rock and roll.

00:09:58.900 --> 00:10:00.260
There's just
a couple of things.

00:10:00.260 --> 00:10:03.960
Part of what you
are blunt about
is yourself.

00:10:03.960 --> 00:10:05.230
Blunt, blunt.

00:10:05.230 --> 00:10:07.760
When you worked in
New Zealand with
a brewery

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:10.000
Lyon Nathan, which had
some hard times

00:10:10.000 --> 00:10:12.460
you were quoted as saying
about yourself--

00:10:12.460 --> 00:10:13.730
this is you
speaking--

00:10:13.730 --> 00:10:16.160
"I was crap for my
last three years.

00:10:16.160 --> 00:10:18.930
I was entrenched,
conservative and
risk-averse."

00:10:18.930 --> 00:10:21.230
How, given your personality,
could that have happened?

00:10:21.230 --> 00:10:22.960
And what lessons should
these young folks

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:24.830
take from the fact that,
by your own measure

00:10:24.830 --> 00:10:27.130
you found yourself
in a position where
you weren't you.

00:10:27.130 --> 00:10:29.100
First of all, never let
a C.E.O. stay around

00:10:29.100 --> 00:10:31.360
for more than seven years--
shoot him.

00:10:31.360 --> 00:10:32.960
Because, you know,
year one you spend

00:10:32.960 --> 00:10:34.660
kind of getting really
excited about it

00:10:34.660 --> 00:10:36.400
learning who people are.

00:10:36.400 --> 00:10:38.460
Year two, you learn a bit
about the business.

00:10:38.460 --> 00:10:40.300
Year three, you start
having some ideas.

00:10:40.300 --> 00:10:41.900
Year four, you start
executing them.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:44.160
Year five, they start
coming to fruition.

00:10:44.160 --> 00:10:46.900
Year six, you start believing
your own bullshit.

00:10:46.900 --> 00:10:49.760
And year seven, you start
defending it, right?

00:10:49.760 --> 00:10:52.100
So, if a C.E.O. has
been there for...

00:10:52.100 --> 00:10:55.700
how long has the guy
who's going to be on
next been here?

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:57.260
Well, shorter than you.

00:10:57.260 --> 00:10:59.100
Okay, that's good then.

00:10:59.100 --> 00:11:03.200
Anyway, once they're there
seven years, show them
the door, man.

00:11:03.200 --> 00:11:06.130
Give them lots of money,
whatever, show them the door.

00:11:06.130 --> 00:11:07.860
Rule number one;
rule number two--

00:11:07.860 --> 00:11:09.760
never work
in a declining industry.

00:11:09.760 --> 00:11:12.330
Man, it is just too hard,
it is too hard.

00:11:12.330 --> 00:11:14.700
I'm a growth guy,
I'm all about people

00:11:14.700 --> 00:11:16.430
I'm all about taking risks.

00:11:16.430 --> 00:11:18.660
And that gets tougher
and tougher and tougher

00:11:18.660 --> 00:11:20.900
if you are in an industry
which really needs

00:11:20.900 --> 00:11:23.900
process decentralization--
re-engineering, restructuring

00:11:23.900 --> 00:11:25.630
and all
this gobbledygook, right?

00:11:25.630 --> 00:11:27.860
I don't like
closing down stuff, you know?

00:11:27.860 --> 00:11:29.530
So I was really no good at it.

00:11:29.530 --> 00:11:31.800
And I stayed there...

00:11:31.800 --> 00:11:34.800
resisting that because
I didn't want to fail.

00:11:34.800 --> 00:11:37.900
And yet I was failing
more and more every day.

00:11:37.900 --> 00:11:39.960
